[3] Research
Date: Thu 6 Jul 2017
Source: Eurosurveillance [edited]
http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=22830


Abstract: We describe the epidemiology of highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) A(H7N9) based on poultry market environmental surveillance and laboratory-confirmed human cases (n=9) in Guangdong, China. We also compare the epidemiology between human cases of high - and low-pathogenic avian influenza A(H7N9) (n=51) in Guangdong. Case fatality and severity were similar. Touching sick or dead poultry was the most important risk factor for HPAI A(H7N9) infections and should be highlighted for the control of future influenza A(H7N9) epidemics.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

---
Date: Thu 6 Jul 2017
Source: Vaccine [edited]
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/m/pubmed/28668573/


Abstract:
Background: We conducted a phase I/II clinical trial to evaluate the safety and immunogenicity of a Madin-Darby canine kidney (MDCK) cell-grown inactivated H7N9 influenza vaccine for pandemic preparedness purposes.

Methods: Between [7 Apr 2015] and 27 May 2016, healthy adults aged 20-60 years were enrolled sequentially in phase I (n=40) and phase II (n=160) from 3 hospitals in Taiwan and randomized to receive 2 doses of whole-virus H7N9 vaccine (15 or 30μg hemagglutinin antigen (HA) with or without an aluminum hydroxide adjuvant) at 21-day intervals. Safety up to 180 days and changes in hemagglutinin inhibition (HI) titers at 21 days after each vaccination was determined.

Results: Of the 200 randomized subjects, 193 (96.5 percent) received 2 doses of the study vaccine and were included in the intention-to-treat analysis for safety, and 190 (95 percent) were included in the per-protocol analysis for immunogenicity. Most adverse events were mild and transient; no death or vaccine-related serious adverse events were reported. Overall, higher immune responses were observed in the groups administered with 30μgHA formulation than in the other 2 groups administered with 15μgHA formulation. The highest immune response was observed in subjects who received 2 doses of the adjuvanted vaccine containing 30μgHA with HI titer, sero-protection rate, sero-conversion rate, and sero-conversion factor of 36.2, 64.6 percent, 64.6 percent and 5.7, respectively.

Conclusions: Our study demonstrated that the H7N9 influenza vaccine containing 30μgHA with aluminum hydroxide adjuvant was immunogenic and safe in adults aged 20-60 years.

--
